  "prompt": "Why does a salt solution conduct electricity?",
  "response": "A salt solution conducts electricity due to the presence of dissolved ions. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Ionic Dissociation\n- When a salt dissolves in water, it breaks apart into positively charged (cations) and negatively charged (anions) ions\n- For example, NaCl \u2192 Na+ + Cl-\n\n2. Ion Mobility\n- These ions can move freely in solution\n- Water molecules help separate and surround the ions, preventing them from recombining\n\n3. Electrical Conductivity Mechanism\n- Ions act as charge carriers\n- Positive ions (cations) move toward the negative electrode\n- Negative ions (anions) move toward the positive electrode\n- This movement of charged particles allows electric current to flow\n\n4. Concentration Dependence\n- More dissolved salt = more ions = better electrical conductivity\n- Concentration of ions directly affects the solution's ability to conduct electricity\n\n5. Electrolyte Classification\n- Strong electrolytes (like NaCl) completely dissociate into ions\n- Weak electrolytes (like acetic acid) only partially dissociate\n\nKey factors enabling conductivity are ion presence, mobility, and charge, which allow electrical current to pass through the solution.",
